DataCite Public Data File 2024
==============================

1. Introduction
    The DataCite Public Data File contains metadata records in JSON format for all DataCite DOIs in Findable state that were registered up to the end of 2024.
    Records have descriptive metadata for research outputs and resources structured according to the DataCite Metadata Schema and DataCite REST API.
    Records include links to other persistent identifiers (PIDs) for works (DOIs), people (ORCID iDs), and organizations (ROR IDs).
    Use of the DataCite Public Data File is subject to the DataCite Data File Use Policy (available at https://support.datacite.org/docs/datacite-data-file-use-policy).

2. Format
    The Data File is supplied as a TAR archive, containing JSONLines formatted metadata records and CSVs with some supplemental information for easier filtering.
    The folders within the Data File are used to group each record by the month it was last updated, following the convention `updated_YYYY-MM`.
    Inside each folder, individual files are compressed with GZIP, to allow for targeted and/or parallel extraction (see section 4 below).
    Each `part_XXXX.jsonl` file contains up to 10,000 metadata records, one per line, with each line being a valid self-contained JSON document.
    For more information on the data format, please see the DataCite Support page linked in section 6 below.
   
3. Size
    The 2024 Data File contains 72,019,577 metadata records, split across 8034 JSONL files as well as 167 CSV files (one per month), and in total is 347GiB when fully decompressed.

4. Extracting the Data File
    The Data File can be easily decompressed in its entirety by using a tool such as GNU Parallel to handle the extraction of each individual GZIP file. 
    The following steps assume that you are working from a Bash-compatible shell on a Linux computer with the `gzip` and `parallel` packages installed, but may also work in other configurations.
    First, extract all of the files from the TAR archive: `tar -xf DataCite_Public_Data_File_2024.tar`.
    Then use `find` to list the files, and pipe them into parallel: `find . -name "*.gz" | parallel gunzip`.
    This will extract the contents of the Data File in situ, replacing the gzipped files with their decompressed versions.

5. Querying the Data File using `jq`
    One efficient way to query data from the Data File is to use a command line JSON tool such as `jq` (https://jqlang.github.io/jq/).
    A simple approach is to read the JSONL files and pipe them into `jq` directly, allowing usage of filters and then selection of relevant attributes.
    The following query will page through the entire Data File and extract records for objects published in 2024, and then select the DOI, URL, and the first listed Title:
    `cat dois/**/*.jsonl | jq '.attributes | select(.publicationYear == 2024) | {doi, url, title: .titles[0].title}'`
    The output from this command could then be redirected to a separate file (e.g, by appending ` > my_records.json` to the end of the previous command).
    Further optimization of this pattern could be achieved by using parallel processing of the JSONL files, rather than reading them sequentially using `cat`.

6. Further Support
    For more information about the Data File, please see the DataCite Support page here: https://support.datacite.org/docs/datacite-public-data-file or email support@datacite.org.
